aws::graph::propositions: # Maule M-7-260C Aircraft Accident Information
The accident involved a takeoff-rejected takeoff.
The defining event of the accident was landing gear collapse.
The pilot held a Private certificate.
The pilot was 48 years old.
The pilot had Single-engine land airplane rating.
The pilot occupied the left seat.
The pilot had no other aircraft ratings.
The pilot used a 3-point restraint.
The pilot had no instrument ratings.
No second pilot was present during the accident.
The pilot had no instructor ratings.
No toxicology was performed on the pilot.
The pilot held Class 3 medical certification with waivers/limitations.
The pilot's last FAA medical exam was on February 20, 2013.
The pilot was not an occupational pilot.
The pilot's last flight review or equivalent was on May 24, 2012.
The pilot had 1413 total flight hours across all aircraft.
The pilot had 98 flight hours in this make and model.
The pilot had 1114 Pilot In Command hours across all aircraft.
The pilot had 40 flight hours in the last 90 days across all aircraft.
The pilot had 21 flight hours in the last 30 days across all aircraft.
The aircraft was a Maule M-7-260C.
The aircraft registration was N5515V.
The aircraft category was Airplane.
The aircraft had a Normal airworthiness certificate.
The aircraft serial number was 30023C.
The aircraft had a tailwheel landing gear type.
The aircraft had 5 seats.
The aircraft's last inspection was an Annual inspection on July 24, 2013.
The aircraft's certified maximum gross weight was 2500 lbs.
The aircraft had 12 hours since the last inspection.
The aircraft had 1 reciprocating engine.
The aircraft's airframe total time was 573.5 hours at the time of accident.
The engine manufacturer was LYCOMING.
The aircraft had an Emergency Locator Transmitter (ELT) installed and activated, but it did not aid in locating the accident.
The engine model/series was IO-540 SER.
The engine was rated at 300 Horsepower.
No operating certificates were held by the operator.
